definition.value: A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 15-oxoprostaglandin F2alpha, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 13,14-dihydro-15-keto-PGF1alpha, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A cyclitol ether that is D-myo-inositol carrying methyl and alpha-D-galactosyl substituents at positions 4 and 3 respectively.
A hydroxyisoflavanone that is dihydrogenistein in which the phenolic hydrogen at position 7 has been replaced by a beta-D-glucosyl residue.
An N-acetylamino-acid residue derived from N-acetyl-L-methionine.
An O-(S-acylpantetheine-4'-phosphoryl)serine(1-) residue in which the S-acyl group is specified as malonamoyl.
A myo-inositol bisphosphate in which the two phosphate groups are located at positions 2 and 4.
An O-(S-acylpantetheine-4'-phosphoryl)serine(1-) residue in which the S-acyl group is specified as 18-carbamoyl-3,5,7,9,11,13,15,17-octaoxooctadecanoyl.
A member of the class of indoles that is glyoxal in which one of the hydrogens has been replaced by an indol-3-yl group.
A 2-acylphloroglucinol in which the acyl group is specified as isobutyryl.

A triterpenoid saponin that is composed of soyasapogenol A having an alpha-L-rhamnopyranosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-galactopyranosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-glucopyranosiduronic acid moiety attached at the 3-position via a glycosidic linkage.
Conjugate base of prostaglandin F1alpha.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of prostaglandin F3alpha, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of prostaglandin A3, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 13,14-dihydro-Delta(12)-prostaglandin J2, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of prostaglandin B3, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An ammonio aldehyde that is an aliphatic aldehyde in which one of the hydrogens of the terminal methyl group has been replaced by an ammonio group. NH3(+)CH2(CH2)nCHO, where n = 0, 1, 2, etc.
A galactoglycerolipid that consists of 3-(3-O-sulfo-beta-D-galactosyl)-sn-glycerol in which the glycerol portion is alkylated at position 1 by a pentyl group.
The alpha-anomer of dTDP-L-rhamnose.
An L-alanine derivative in which one of the methyl hydrogens of N-acetyl-L-alanine has been replaced by an (S)-allylsulfinyl group.
An alpha-amino-acid anion that is the conjugate base of N-acetylalliin, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.

A 1-acyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine zwitterion obtained by transfer of a proton from the amino to the phosphate group of 1-docosahexaenoyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphoethanolamine; major species at pH 7.3.
A leukotriene anion that is the conjugate base of leukotriene E4 obtained by deprotonation of the two carboxy groups and protonation of the cysteinyl alpha-amino group; major species at pH 7.3.
A leukotriene anion that is the conjugate base of 20,20,20-trihydroxyleukotriene B4, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteine in which the S-substitutuent is specified as 5-acetamido-2-hydroxyphenyl.
A leukotriene anion that is the conjugate base of 12,20-dioxoleukotriene B4, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A leukotriene anion that is the conjugate base of 20,20-dihydroxyleukotriene B4, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An S-substituted N-acetyl-L-cysteine that is the conjugate base of S-(5-acetamido-2-hydroxyphenyl)-N-acetyl-L-cysteine, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
A leukotriene anion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups and protonation of the cysteinyl alpha-amino group of 20-carboxyleukotriene E4; major species at pH 7.3.
A leukotriene anion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups and protonation of the glutathionyl alpha-amino group of 11,12-dihydro-12-oxoleukotriene C4; major species at pH 7.3.
A leukotriene anion obtained by deprotonation of the three carboxy groups and protonation of the glutathionyl alpha-amino group of 11,12-dihydro-(12R)-hydroxyleukotriene C4; major species at pH 7.3.
An amino-acid cation residue obtained by protonation of the side-chain amino group of (5R)-5-hydroxy-L-lysine residue residue; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid cation residue obtained by protonation of the side-chain amino group of (5R)-5-(beta-D-galactosyloxy)-L-lysine residue; major species at pH 7.3.
Any ceramide in which the primary hydroxy hydrogen has been replaced by an acyl group.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the R is a saturated fatty acyl chain.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the R is a monounsaturated fatty acyl chain.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the R group is a methyl-branched fatty acyl chain.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any oxo-fatty acid with the hydroxy group of L-carnitine.
An O-acylcarnitine in which the R group is a hydroxylated fatty acyl chain.
An O-acyl-L-carnitine obtained by formal condensation of the carboxy group of any 2-enoic acid with the hydroxy group of L-carnitine.
A prostaglandin carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 6-oxoprostaglandin F1alpha, obtained by deprotonation of the carboxy group; major species at pH 7.3.
An alpha-amino-acid cation residue obtained by protonation of the side-chain amino group of (5R)-5-[(alpha-D-glucosyl-(1->2)-beta-D-galactosyl)oxy]-L-lysine residue; major species at pH 7.3.

An oligosaccharide phosphate consisting of D-myo-inositol having a 6-O-(2-aminoethylphosphono)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->2)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->6)-alpha-D-mannosyl-(1->4)-alpha-D-glucosaminyl residue attached at the 6-position.

An alkylamino group derived from 6-O-(2-aminoethylphosphono)-alpha-D-Man-(1->2)-alpha-D-Man-(1->6)-alpha-D-Man-(1->4)-alpha-D-GlcN-(1->6)-D-myo-inositol where the point of attachment is on the primary amino function of the ethanolamine phosphate moiety.
A dec-2-enal in which the olefinic double bond has E configuration.
A PC(18:3/0:0) in which the 1-acyl group is specified as alpha-linolenoyl.
An enone that is (E)-3-nonene in which the two methylene hydrogens at position 2 have been replaced by an oxo group.
A member of the class of naphthalenes that is naproxen in which the methoxy group has been replaced by a sulfooxy group.
An organic anion obtained by deprotonation of at least one of the acidic functions of desmethylnaproxen sulfate.
